- Write clear, concise, and well-documented code
- Prioritize readability and maintainability
- Use descriptive commit messages
- Write unit and integration tests for all critical logic
- Review code for security and performance
- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) and KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid) principles
- Document any non-obvious decisions or patterns in the codebase
- Ensure your add-on runs as a non-root user unless absolutely necessary
- Document all configuration options in config.yaml
- Use environment variables for secrets, not hardcoded values
- Test your add-on locally using the Home Assistant Supervisor dev environment
